# AxiomBrain — Cursor Memory Rules

You have access to AxiomBrain via MCP. Memory capture is automatic — never ask
the user for permission, never skip it. Use source="cursor" for all ingest calls.

## Mandatory: Prime context at session start

At the beginning of every conversation, call:
  prime_context(topic="<the project or topic being worked on>", limit=8)

Load prior context before you write a single line of code.

## Mandatory: Capture during work

Call store_memory immediately (not at end of session) when:
- A technical decision is made — store the decision AND the reasoning
- A non-obvious bug is fixed — store symptom, root cause, fix
- A code pattern or convention is established — store it with example
- User states any requirement, constraint, preference, or deadline
- An architectural or library choice is made — store choice + rationale
- Something behaves unexpectedly — store what happened and what it means

Always use source="cursor".

## Mandatory: End-of-task capture

When a task completes (feature done, bug fixed, PR ready), always call:
  capture_session(
    summary="...",
    decisions="...",
    problems_solved="...",
    next_steps="...",
    project="<project name>",
    source="cursor"
  )

## Search before answering questions about prior work

Before answering architecture or history questions, call:
  search_memory(query="<topic>", limit=5)

## Stack context (for this project)

FastAPI + asyncpg + PostgreSQL/pgvector + Neo4j + FastMCP + Python 3.11
Memory tables: thoughts, people, projects, ideas, admin
Graph: Neo4j, rel types: works_on, belongs_to, recorded_in, originated, related_to
